After these remarks as to the viscera had been written, a treatise on the pancreatic juice published by the eminent Ragnar. de Graaf came into my hands, in which that learned man most clearly proves the existence ol the pancreatic juice, and confirms the use which I have assigned to it. But it is scarcely credible that healthy pancreatic juice is of an acid nature: noris it likely that the effervescence taking place when that juice is mixed with bile in the intestines is caused by the aeid salt of the pancreatic juice meeting the fixed or the volatile salt of which the bile consists, as is the opinion ol the learned author3 for the effervescence of contrary salts does not seem suitable to the animal economy inasmuch as it comes quickly to an end and is always ac· companied by coagulation, as has been stated above.
